<paper id="1587779614"><title>On logics, tilings, and automata</title><year>1991</year><authors><author org="Christian-Albrechts-Universität, Kiel," id="2121581756">Wolfgang Thomas</author></authors><n_citation>78</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>89538287</reference><reference>1597502208</reference><reference>1705394006</reference><reference>1829669836</reference><reference>1971416129</reference><reference>1973576343</reference><reference>2074048601</reference><reference>2085533703</reference><reference>2131663704</reference><reference>2132295002</reference><reference>2157390113</reference><reference>2331953749</reference><reference>2401216365</reference></references><venue id="1141821850" type="C">International Colloquium on Automata, Languages and Programming</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-54233-7_154</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.62961">Quantum finite automata</keyword><keyword weight="0.45418">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.64748">Automata theory</keyword><keyword weight="0.49704">Logical conjunction</keyword><keyword weight="0.62287">Nested word</keyword><keyword weight="0.41867">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.56934">Decidability</keyword><keyword weight="0.49597">Pushdown automaton</keyword><keyword weight="0.51392">Tree automaton</keyword><keyword weight="0.60399">ω-automaton</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We relate the logical and the automata theoretic approach to define sets of words, trees, and graphs. For this purpose a notion of “graph acceptor” is introduced which can specify monadic second-order properties and allows to treat known types of finite automata in a common framework. In the final part of the paper, we discuss infinite graphs that have a decidable monadic second-order theory.</abstract></paper>